    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im studying for my materials class and im a bit confused. why do we actually need to put steel rebar inside concrete for foundations? i get that concrete is strong, but whats the deal with the relationship between its compressive strength and the tensile strength of the steel? like why do they need each other?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Concrete excels at handling compression, but it is inherently very weak when subjected to tension, which is a major stress in foundations. Steel rebar provides the necessary tensile strength, acting as the skeleton that resists those pulling forces. By combining these materials, engineers create reinforced concrete, a composite material where the steel handles the tension and the concrete handles the compression. This synergy makes the foundation robust enough to withstand real-world loads.",
      "source": "target",
