    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok so if we don't compact it right and those voids stay in there, is it like a structural failure waiting to happen? what actually happens to the load path if the concrete and the steel aren't touching properly in certain spots?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If voids persist and the concrete isn't properly bonded to the rebar, the load path is broken in those areas. Instead of distributing stress uniformly between the two materials, the load concentrates excessively onto the continuous concrete areas, leading to premature localized failure. In severe cases, this can create stress risers, initiating cracks and accelerating structural deterioration well before the design capacity is reached.",
      "source": "target",
